The plaque is — *brass.* It is screwed into the wall of the narthex. I walk past it every Sunday. *In grateful recognition.* And the book — *the book in my hand* — says — *Son, remember that thou in thy lifetime —*

*A long break. His voice has gone almost to nothing.*

I cannot hold both. Friend. I cannot — I have tried all day. I have tried for years. I cannot hold both. One of them is wrong. *One of them is wrong* and I have been — I have been sitting under the wrong one. Every Sunday. Under the roof. Under the plaque. Singing the hymn.

*His hands close on the stones. Open again.*

I am a high school history teacher. I teach children about abolitionists with this passage in my mouth. *And on Sunday I sit under the plaque.*

*He looks up at the sky. Then down. Then he is not speaking to the player anymore. He is speaking past him.*

I can't. I can't say it. The text says it and I — *I am not the one who says it.* I am not — I do not have — *the office.* I do not have the office, friend, I am a Sunday school teacher with a paper cup, I am — 

*A breath. And then very quietly:*

Doctor Luther.

*Quieter:*

Doctor Luther. I can't do this.

*A long pause. His head goes down.*

Come and say what I cannot.

